            <ce:date-received day="3" month="4" year="2025"/>
            <ce:date-revised day="6" month="6" year="2025"/>
            <ce:date-accepted day="8" month="6" year="2025"/>
            
            <ce:abstract class="author" id="ab010" view="all"><ce:abstract-sec id="as010" view="all">
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0010" view="all">Bird population monitoring is crucial for understanding biodiversity trends, with various methods differing in effectiveness. This study compared traditional observer-based methods, including point counts and manual analysis of passive acoustic monitoring (PAM) recordings, with automated species detection using BirdNET during springtime in a European primaeval forest, Białowieża National Park in Poland. We evaluated 97 10-minute surveys from each method and input all-day recordings into BirdNET to explore the differences in alpha richness and beta diversity at both the survey level and cumulative over the entire breeding season.</ce:simple-para>
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0015" view="all">The results show that BirdNET detected the highest alpha richness (80 species) when processing all-day recordings. However, its performance during short-term surveys was lower (49 species) compared to that of human observers, with recording analysis yielding the highest species count among the observer-based methods (61 species). Beta diversity also differed according to the site and method used (p &lt; 0.05). The number of species detected during all short-term surveys showed a weak correlation with the number of species obtained from all-day BirdNET analysis (Pearson’s correlation: 0.34–0.49), questioning the adequacy of short-term surveys in species-rich habitats such as primaeval forests.</ce:simple-para>
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0020" view="all">Our findings demonstrate that monitoring methods should be adjusted to improve coverage. Automated analysis offers scalability and efficiency but still requires significant time dedicated to processing, so manual review remains essential for validating automated classifications and ensuring data accuracy. On the other hand, point counts and recording analysis can provide valuable insights in situations where time is limited or when finer verification of species detection is necessary.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:abstract-sec></ce:abstract>
            <ce:keywords class="keyword" id="kg005" view="all">
               <ce:section-title id="st015">Keywords</ce:section-title>
               <ce:keyword id="k0005">
                  <ce:text>Passive acoustic monitoring</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="k0010">
                  <ce:text>Detection method</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="k0015">
                  <ce:text>Acoustic surveys</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="k0020">
                  <ce:text>Point counts</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="k0025">
                  <ce:text>Automated analysis</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="k0030">
                  <ce:text>BirdNET</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
            </ce:keywords>
            <ce:data-availability id="da005" view="all">
               <ce:section-title id="st020">Data availability</ce:section-title>
               <ce:para id="p0030" view="all">We have shared the data in Zenodo repository at <ce:inter-ref xlink:href="https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.15610652" id="ir9292" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/linking-roles/research-data">https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.15610652</ce:inter-ref>.</ce:para>
            </ce:data-availability>
         </head>
         <body view="all">
            <ce:sections>
               <ce:section id="s0005" view="all">
                  <ce:label>1</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="st025">Introduction</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0035" view="all">Species monitoring is used to evaluate spatial and temporal patterns in biological diversity (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0125" id="c0055">Moussy et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>), which is especially valuable in times of increasingly frequent anthropogenic disturbances and rapid climate change that accelerate both species loss and expansion (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0110 b0160" id="r0005">Lepetz et al., 2009; Stewart et al., 2022</ce:cross-refs>). For this reason, monitoring efforts must be as precise as possible to eliminate potential biases that may lead to under- or overestimation of abundance or other population parameters. One of the most pressing challenges in species assessments is that not all species are recorded and rare or elusive species are often overlooked due to their cryptic nature (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0095 b0070" id="r0010">Kéry and Schmid, 2006; Hending, 2025</ce:cross-refs>). While various organism groups can be monitored, birds are among the most studied taxa (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0125" id="c0060">Moussy et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>), likely due to the ease of their detection and the wealth of existing knowledge about them. They are also considered reliable indicators of overall biodiversity (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0105 b0135" id="r0015">Larsen et al., 2012; Natsukawa and Sergio, 2022</ce:cross-refs>).</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0040" view="all">Currently, the most common method for gathering information on bird species inhabiting a given area is point counts. During these surveys, the observer records all species seen or heard from a fixed point over a set period, usually from about 5 to 20 min, within either an unlimited or (better) fixed radius. This duration is believed to be sufficiently long to obtain a somewhat representative sample of species richness from that site (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0010 b0015" id="r0020">Bibby et al., 1992; Bonthoux and Balent, 2012</ce:cross-refs>). The main advantage of point counts is that they are simple, broadly applicable, and efficient for estimating bird diversity. Point counts are also well suited for detecting non-vocalising species such as raptors. However, they are also highly observer- and distance-dependent (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0005 b0055" id="r0025">Alldredge et al., 2007; Farmer et al., 2012</ce:cross-refs>), have low repeatability, and, due to (usually) short durations, may overlook rarely vocalising species. However, there are also other methods of obtaining species data from study sites, one of which is recording vocal activity.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0045" view="all">Passive acoustic monitoring (PAM) is an innovative approach to studying soundscapes and the vocal behaviour of various animal taxa. It utilises autonomous recording units (ARUs) deployed in the field to record soundscapes over extended periods. These devices are programmable, allowing researchers to gather extensive data with minimal supervision, aside from occasional battery or memory card changes (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0065" id="c0065">Gibb et al., 2019</ce:cross-ref>). PAM has proven suitable for diversified research, such as gathering information on bird species richness (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0035" id="c0070">Darras et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>) or species density (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0145" id="c0075">Pérez-Granados and Traba, 2021</ce:cross-ref>) using microphone arrays. Traditionally, PAM data processing involves identifying species manually by listening to audio recordings or examining spectrograms (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0165" id="c0080">Sugai et al., 2019</ce:cross-ref>), which are visual representations of recorded sounds. However, this approach requires extensive and time-consuming analysis to identify species from the recordings, and its accuracy depends on the recordings' quality and background noise level. Recent advancements in automated analysis tools have significantly improved the efficiency of sound analysis, allowing for the automatic processing of far more data than human surveyors alone can (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0185" id="c0085">Ware et al., 2023</ce:cross-ref>). Despite this progress, automated tools are still under development and generally are not as precise as manual analysis, still requiring human verification for accurate results.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0050" view="all">While various automated tools are gaining popularity, BirdNET (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0090" id="c0090">Kahl et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>) is one of the most widely used nowadays. It is a tool for analysing sounds using machine learning models by dividing the spectrograms into 3-second interval samples and based on their similarity to trained samples, identifies species with a confidence score between 0 and 1 (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0090" id="c0095">Kahl et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>), with values closer to 1 indicating a higher level of confidence in species classification (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0200" id="c0100">Wood and Kahl, 2024</ce:cross-ref>). As of today, BirdNET can recognise over 6000 species (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0200" id="c0105">Wood and Kahl, 2024</ce:cross-ref>), and it has already been proven to maximise species counts when combined with human observers (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0185" id="c0110">Ware et al., 2023</ce:cross-ref>) due to the extended sampling period. Previously, many studies have compared point count surveys with PAM and found that they yield different outcomes (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0075" id="c0115">Hoefer et al., 2023</ce:cross-ref>). Most studies indicate no differences between methods, the superiority of PAM over observer counts in the long term or propose combining the two methods for the best results (e.g. <ce:cross-refs refid="b0100 b0040 b0030 b0050" id="r0030">Klingbeil and Willig, 2015; Darras et al., 2019; Budka et al., 2021; Drake et al., 2021</ce:cross-refs>). Thus, automatic tools appear to greatly enhance bird monitoring efforts, providing a more comprehensive assessment of the species composition of study sites. Nevertheless, automated methods rely heavily on the quality of the training data and recordings (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0090" id="c0120">Kahl et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>), which is often compromised in the case of soundscape recordings obtained through PAM. The results are also difficult to compare, as the algorithms yield different outcomes depending on the recordings and species, even within the same area (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0200" id="c0125">Wood and Kahl, 2024</ce:cross-ref>), and their effectiveness depends on environmental conditions during the surveys, as well as species richness and densities in surveyed areas.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0055" view="all">In this study, we compare survey methods across the entire breeding season, providing a cumulative assessment of alpha richness and beta diversity. This approach advances our understanding of method effectiveness over time, highlighting differences in long-term detection outcomes and assessing the value of automated surveys for robust and scalable biodiversity monitoring. We aim to (i) evaluate the performance of point counts and passive acoustic surveys with automatic detection methods and (ii) identify factors influencing detection differences between methods. To achieve this, we conducted 10-minute point counts and simultaneously recorded soundscapes in the remnants of a European primaeval forest, Białowieża National Park, to compare them with manual and automated species identification from recording samples. Additionally, we processed daylong recordings using BirdNET from the same set of sites and days to compare alpha richness estimates across methods and evaluate the impact of short sampling periods on detection outcomes. We hypothesised that point count surveys would record fewer species than recording analyses, as recordings can be analysed more thoroughly, while observers only have a short opportunity to detect each species in the field. We predicted that BirdNET, when applied to 10-minute recordings, would detect the fewest species and consequently show the lowest levels of alpha richness due to the algorithm’s limitations. On the other hand, we expected that BirdNET applied to all-day recordings would detect the highest alpha richness, surpassing any of the 10-minute surveys, as longer recording durations provide greater opportunities for capturing additional species.</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="s0010" view="all">
                  <ce:label>2</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="st030">Material and methods</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0060" view="all">The study was conducted in 2022 in the central part of the Białowieża National Park in Poland (52°42′57.6″ N 23°50′42.0″ E), a primaeval temperate forest with a ∼6000 ha reserve that has been under strict protection since 1921. This distinctive area has been the subject of comprehensive research for decades (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0025" id="c0130">Broughton et al., 2025</ce:cross-ref>), including 50 years of annual avian censuses providing long-term data on species presence and abundance (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0190" id="c0135">Wesołowski et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0065" view="all">The study was performed across five permanent sites established in 1975 in the Reserve (<ce:cross-ref refid="f0005" id="c0140">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref>
                     <ce:float-anchor refid="f0005"/>; <ce:cross-ref refid="b0175" id="c0145">Tomiałojć et al., 1984</ce:cross-ref>). These sites span three forest habitats; ash-alder riverine forest (site K, 33 ha), lime-hornbeam forest (W 25.5 ha, C 24 ha, and M 30 ha) and pine-bilberry coniferous forest (NW 25 ha, NE 25 ha, adjacent and pooled into a single site, hereafter N) (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0190" id="c0150">Wesołowski et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>). At each site, we randomly selected from 3 to 5 points separated by at least 350 m (20 points in total), where we conducted the surveys. During the study year, distance sampling point count surveys by experienced observers (JB, MC, GN, in an alternating order of site visits to minimise observer effect) started on 30th March and ended on 1st June. Each study point was visited five times, once every two weeks. Surveys began after sunrise, with the earliest starting at 4:34 a.m. and the latest starting at 10:17 a.m. During each visit, 10-minute point counts were performed, with observers recording all species heard or seen. The observer remained at a fixed location throughout each survey, categorising all birds into three predefined distance classes based on their observations. These surveys are referred to as the point counts in the manuscript.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0070" view="all">Before the start of the censuses, we placed automated recorders (Song Meter SM4 with two built-in omnidirectional microphones with a sensitivity of −35 ± 4 dB and a signal-to-noise ratio of 80 dB; Wildlife Acoustics, USA) at each study point. Before recording started, the microphone sensitivity was calibrated using a VOLTCRAFT SLC-100 sound level calibrator. ARUs were mounted on tree trunks at a height of approximately 8 m, up to a few meters from the counting point. Recorders were scheduled to operate for 8 to 9 days during the anticipated survey period (adjusted for weather conditions), recording for at least 15 h a day, starting from 1 h before sunrise to 1 h after sunset. Due to technical difficulties, one device was non-operational for 3 weeks (M census site), resulting in only two recorded surveys (hence 97 total surveys). Sound files were saved as uncompressed 60-minute PCM.wav files with a 48 kHz sampling rate, gain at 16 dB and 16-bit resolution, with no high- or low-pass filters applied. Meteorological data on the mean daily temperature (˚C), humidity (%) and wind (m/s) were obtained from the public data repository of the Institute of Meteorology and Water Management of the National Research Institute and the Białowieża station (<ce:inter-ref xlink:href="https://dane.imgw.pl" xlink:type="simple" id="ir010">https://dane.imgw.pl</ce:inter-ref>). This station is located approximately 1 km from the nearest point and about 6.3 km from the farthest point.</ce:para>
                  <ce:section id="s0015" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.1</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st035">Acoustic analysis</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0075" view="all">For the acoustic analysis, we performed a blind analysis on 97 10-minute recordings concurrent with the point counts conducted by observers. All files were anonymised and partitioned into four sets of approximately 50 recordings, with blind analysis conducted independently by DW, PS, MB, and TO, each analysing one set. We identified all species either by listening to the recordings or by visually analysing the spectrograms using the same settings in the Raven Pro software (version 1.6.5, <ce:cross-ref refid="b0085" id="c0155">K. Lisa Yang Center for Conservation Bioacoustics, 2025</ce:cross-ref>), with the Grayscale colour set, brightness set to 60, contrast set to 50, and FFT set to 1024 samples. Subsequently, we cross-validated sets among four observers, allowing each to confirm identifications and potentially identify species that had been previously overlooked. In the manuscript, this is referred to as PAM-MA (manual analysis), with both point counts and PAM-MA categorised as observer-based surveys.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0080" view="all">For the automated analyses, we input the same 10-minute recordings to BirdNET (version 2.2) integrated into Raven Pro software. We adjusted the segment overlap (set to 1s) and the threshold value (default 0.25) to increase the number of detections and the probability of correct detections. Additionally, we opted for the global list of species, as it yielded better detections than the European species list. BirdNET detections were manually verified, and only true positives, meaning correctly identified species, were counted. This is referred to as the PAM-BN (BirdNET 10-minute analysis) in the manuscript.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0085" view="all">We also analysed the entire set of daylong-hour recordings from the survey days. Of 1739 one-hour files, 14 were damaged and, therefore, omitted, resulting in 1725 files for analysis. Due to the recording schedule and longer days towards the end of the season, daily files included between 15 and 19 h of recordings. We manually reviewed the detections provided by BirdNET<ce:hsp sp="0.25"/>and, for each species, marked only the first true positive detection with the highest confidence score per survey day, regardless of the number of detections for this species. We also cross-validated uncertain detections, which included species that were challenging to recognise or unexpected for the study area. This is referred to as BN ALL (BirdNET all-day analysis) within the manuscript. The algorithm’s precision was calculated as the ratio of correctly classified BirdNET species detections (true positives) to the total number of species proposed by the software <ce:cross-ref refid="f0025" id="c0160">Fig. 5</ce:cross-ref>.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="s0020" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.2</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st040">Statistical analysis</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0090" view="all">All analyses were performed in R version 4.4.2 (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0150" id="c0165">R Core Team, 2024</ce:cross-ref>). To test the differences in accumulated alpha richness between each detection method, we created a generalised linear mixed model (GLMM) with a Gaussian distribution and identity link function using the ‘glmmTMB’ package (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0020" id="c0170">Brooks et al., 2017</ce:cross-ref>). The response variable was the cumulative number of species at each point, while the explanatory variable was the detection method (BN ALL, Point count, PAM-MA, PAM-BN). Additionally, we incorporated the site as a random factor to account for variation in survey locations.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0095" view="all">To investigate how the method influenced alpha richness detected during each survey, we used another GLMM with a Gaussian distribution and an identity link. To avoid including correlated variables, we tested the environmental characteristics for multicollinearity prior to the analysis, and their<ce:hsp sp="0.25"/>variance inflation factor (VIF) was no greater than 1.15, except for the temperature, which was removed from the model due to its correlation with the survey date. The response variable was the number of species obtained with each method at each survey, whereas the explanatory variables included the interaction terms between the detection method (four-level factor: BN ALL vs Point count vs PAM-MA vs PAM-BN) and all other predictors: survey date, time of survey start, and weather variables, including wind (m/s) and humidity (%). We also included the observer from the<ce:hsp sp="0.25"/>point count survey and the site as random factors.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0100" view="all">We tested the correlation between the number of species detected by each method using Pearson's correlation and used the Tukey post-hoc pairwise comparison test to compare the methods and sites. To compare species composition recorded with each method among sites, we calculated beta diversity using the ‘vegan’ package (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0140" id="c0175">Oksanen et al., 2024</ce:cross-ref>), applying the Bray-Curtis dissimilarity metric. Within the manuscript, mean values are given with ±standard deviation.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="s0025" view="all">
                  <ce:label>3</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="st045">Results</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0105" view="all">Using BirdNET on full-day recordings resulted in the detection of the most species (80 true positive species out of 1826 total proposed species identified from the global list, achieving a precision of 4.38 %). In short-term surveys, PAM-MA detected up to 61 species, accounting for 76.3 % of the total 80 species observed during full-day recordings, with an average of 12.8 ± 4.2 species per 10-minute recording. Point counts detected 53 species, representing 66.3 % of all species, with an average of 11.3 ± 2.9 species per survey. BirdNET identified 49 species, 61.3 % of the total detected species, detecting an average of only 6.3 ± 2.54 species per recording.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0110" view="all">When comparing the cumulative number of species per point, all methods detected significantly fewer species than BN ALL, with PAM-BN detecting the least (β = −0.57, p &lt; 0.01; <ce:cross-ref refid="t0005" id="c0180">Table 1</ce:cross-ref>
                     <ce:float-anchor refid="t0005"/>) and PAM-MA detecting the most (β = −0.40, p &lt; 0.01). At the survey level, the model revealed consistent patterns, with all methods detecting fewer species than BN ALL, similar to the cumulative results. Among them, PAM-MA missed the fewest species<ce:hsp sp="0.25"/>(β = −0.42, p &lt; 0.01; <ce:cross-ref refid="s0070" id="c0185">Table S1</ce:cross-ref>), and PAM-BN missed the most (β = −0.63, p &lt; 0.01). The survey date showed a significant positive effect on detections across all short-term survey methods (β = 0.12, p &lt; 0.01), with short-term survey detections increasing as the season progressed. However, it reduced detections in BN ALL analysis, with fewer species detected as the season advanced (β = −0.13, p &lt; 0.001). Among environmental variables, higher humidity was linked to fewer detections in general (β = −0.09, p &lt; 0.01), while the wind negatively affected the PAM-MA method with fewer detections on windier days (β =  −0.12, p &lt; 0.05).</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0115" view="all">All methods significantly differed in the Tukey post-hoc pairwise comparison test (<ce:cross-ref refid="s0070" id="c0190">Table S2</ce:cross-ref>; p &lt; 0.001), except for PAM-MA and point counts in their cumulative alpha richness. Among all short-term methods, PAM-MA resulted in the highest number of species detected, while point counts yielded more species detections than automated analysis.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0120" view="all">The number of species obtained using different methods was not strongly correlated (<ce:cross-ref refid="f0010" id="c0195">Fig. 2</ce:cross-ref>
                     <ce:float-anchor refid="f0010"/>), except for the cumulative alpha richness detected with PAM-MA and PAM-BN (Pearson’s correlation: r = 0.75, p &lt; 0.001). At the survey level, a moderate correlation was observed between PAM-MA analysis and PAM-BN (0.53, p &lt; 0.001).</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0125" view="all">BirdNET detections were highest at the beginning of the study and declined over time, whereas observer-based methods recorded the most observations in the middle of the breeding season (<ce:cross-ref refid="f0015" id="c0200">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>
                     <ce:float-anchor refid="f0015"/>). This pattern was consistent across all habitats, except at site N, where BN ALL peaked mid-season, and at sites K and W, where point count observers detected fewer species during the same period. Significant differences in species composition between sites were observed only when using automated methods at the survey level (<ce:cross-ref refid="s0070" id="c0205">Table S3</ce:cross-ref>), with the greatest variation observed between the riverine forest and lime-hornbeam forest. Survey method and its interaction with site significantly affected beta diversity estimates (p &lt; 0.05; <ce:cross-ref refid="s0070" id="c0210">Table S4</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0130" view="all">The number of species detected varied with the method used; a complete list of detected bird species is provided in <ce:cross-ref refid="s0070" id="c0215">Table S5</ce:cross-ref>. Manual methods showed consistency in detecting similar species across different habitats (<ce:cross-ref refid="f0020" id="c0220">Fig. 4</ce:cross-ref>
                     <ce:float-anchor refid="f0020"/>). In particular, the number of species detected by observers in the field was in line with PAM-MA and grouped very well. Point count observers and PAM-MA recorded Common Chaffinches <ce:italic>Fringilla coelebs</ce:italic>, Blackbirds <ce:italic>Turdus merula</ce:italic>, and Woodpigeons <ce:italic>Columba palumbus</ce:italic> most frequently. BirdNET on short recordings detected the most Wood Warblers <ce:italic>Phylloscopus sibilatrix</ce:italic>, Common Chaffinches, and Great-spotted Woodpeckers <ce:italic>Dendrocopos major</ce:italic>, whereas all-day BirdNET most frequently detected Hawfinches <ce:italic>Coccothraustes coccothraustes</ce:italic>, Blackbirds, and Woodpigeons. PAM-BN missed only six species observed by on-site observers and 12 species identified with PAM-MA. The species detected at every site and during each day by BN ALL was the Hawfinch (97 detections). During the BN ALL analysis, all species were detected with fairly high scores (over 0.4), regardless of the number of detections (<ce:cross-ref refid="f0025" id="c0225">Fig. 5</ce:cross-ref>
                     <ce:float-anchor refid="f0025"/>).</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="s0030" view="all">
                  <ce:label>4</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="st050">Discussion</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0135" view="all">Our study investigated how different bird monitoring methods affect species detection in a European primaeval forest. We compared traditional observer-based surveys with automated analysis using BirdNET. Our findings highlight the strengths and limitations of each approach. Short-term observer-based surveys, such as point counts and recording analysis, yield similar results. In contrast, automated analysis of longer-duration recordings offers promising potential for large-scale monitoring.</ce:para>
                  <ce:section id="s0035" view="all">
                     <ce:label>4.1</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st055">Point counts and short-period sampling</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0140" view="all">Post-hoc tests revealed significant differences between all detection methods, indicating that more species were detected when manually analysing PAM recordings compared to point counts. Most findings of other bird studies comparing PAM and point counts suggest that PAM produces equal or superior results (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0075" id="c0230">Hoefer et al., 2023</ce:cross-ref>), although some studies report similar outcomes when accounting for detection ranges (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0035" id="c0235">Darras et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>). PAM analysers benefit from the ability to analyse the same vocalisations multiple times, allowing them to detect even faint sounds that on-site observers might miss due to various environmental factors (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0130" id="c0240">Naguib and Wiley, 2001</ce:cross-ref>). Even though on-site observers can identify non-vocalising species, PAM recordings still detected more species. Most of the species undetected by point count observers emitted contact calls that are easy to miss during field visits, but these calls can be easily analysed from PAM recordings. Additionally, since human hearing allows for sound detection over greater distances than PAM (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0060 b0210" id="r0035">Furnas and Callas, 2015; Yip et al., 2017</ce:cross-refs>), placing the ARUs at a higher elevation − where the sound detection range is enhanced (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0045" id="c0245">Darras et al., 2016</ce:cross-ref>) − may have allowed the recorders to capture sounds from farther away, thus balancing the detection chances between observers and PAM.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0145" view="all">As expected, BirdNET detected the fewest species on short recordings. The software is still in development<ce:hsp sp="0.25"/>and varies in effectiveness depending on the species (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0195" id="c0250">Winiarska et al., 2025</ce:cross-ref>). For example, during short surveys, BirdNET most frequently detected the Wood Warbler, a species with distinctive vocalisations that are easily recognisable and difficult to confuse with others. This suggests that automated detection methods are particularly effective for identifying species with clear and unique vocalisations, even within 10-minute recording windows. However, this limited duration may restrict the detection of more subtle or complex sounds that are harder to capture automatically. In contrast, human observers, both during point counts and PAM analysis, primarily identified common species, possibly due to their high abundance in the study sites.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="s0040" view="all">
                     <ce:label>4.2</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st060">BirdNET analysis of all-day recordings</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0150" view="all">As predicted, BirdNET detected the most species when analysing all-day recordings. While the tool identified fewer species in short samples, its effectiveness lies in its capacity to process more data than a<ce:hsp sp="0.25"/>human observer could manage. With longer recordings, the likelihood of capturing vocalisations that are clearer or closer to the device increases (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0205" id="c0255">Wood et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>), enabling the algorithm to detect more species and thus resulting in higher diversity measures (<ce:cross-ref id="c0260" refid="b0120">Metcalf et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>). Additionally, extended recordings reduce or eliminate human disturbances that could influence birds' behaviour, even though recent studies indicate the impact is minimal (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0080" id="c0265">Hutto and Hutto, 2020</ce:cross-ref>). Our results align with a similar study (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0155" id="c0270">Schuster et al., 2024</ce:cross-ref>) in which cumulative surveys of farmland birds also showed the highest species richness for BirdNET; however, point counts eventually surpassed automated methods after 55 days of sampling. Although automated analysis still requires manual validation, it correctly detects more than twice as many species as short-term surveys. Even after summarising results for the entire season, automated methods analysed 15–19 h of recordings per survey, whereas other methods relied on just 10 min—90 to 114 times shorter in duration. In our case, when validating BirdNET's all-day output, each species was only labelled starting from the highest score until the first true positive detection was made, allowing us to reduce the analysis time for a full-day recording to approximately the same duration as manually processing two 10-minute recordings. This approach limited analysis to species with detection scores no lower than 0.4, further enhancing the accuracy of species identification. At the same time, choosing the global list instead of European species lowered the algorithm’s precision, which resulted in an excessive number of proposed species, and the European species list might work better with newer versions of the software. While this study focuses on species richness, it is worth noting that several existing studies have already investigated species-specific thresholds for BirdNET that improve detection accuracy (e.g. <ce:cross-refs refid="b0155 b0180" id="r0040">Schuster et al., 2024; Tseng et al., 2025</ce:cross-refs>). Although a similar study (<ce:cross-ref id="c0275" refid="b0170">Thompson et al., 2025</ce:cross-ref>) found that community composition more closely matched point counts when using species-specific thresholds, using a universal threshold also proved effective when applied to longer recording durations, as we detected all species observed during point counts. Future work could build on this by integrating these thresholds to reduce field validation time and enhance long-term monitoring, providing more detailed data beyond presence-absence, such as species abundance and vocal activity.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0155" view="all">An interesting finding was the low correlation between the number of species detected during short surveys and those identified in all-day BirdNET recordings. This discrepancy likely reflects the differences in monitoring timing and duration, as the all-day recordings allowed for the detection of species that do not typically vocalise during the day, such as the Eurasian woodcock <ce:italic>Scolopax rusticola</ce:italic>, or those that vocalise only in a specific context, such as woodpeckers. These findings raise important questions about the effectiveness of short sampling in accurately reflecting species richness at monitoring sites, especially in habitats where some species are more elusive or vocalise irregularly. However, it is necessary to recognise that alpha richness alone is not a comprehensive measure of biodiversity (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0115" id="c0280">Magurran, 2021</ce:cross-ref>). At present, the ability of PAM to efficiently estimate species densities is limited (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0145" id="c0285">Pérez-Granados and Traba, 2021</ce:cross-ref>), and detection ranges vary across species and detection methods (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0195" id="c0290">Winiarska et al., 2025</ce:cross-ref>). Consequently, species richness in PAM is effectively assessed for an unmeasurable spatial extent, complicating its interpretation.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0160" view="all">Importantly, the time dedicated to each analysis varied considerably. Point counts involved about 70 h of fieldwork, emphasising the intensive effort required for on-site surveys, particularly in terms of time spent in the field. PAM-MA took 50 h, which was less than the point counts, but it still required significant time to annotate the vocalisations and identify species in the recordings. BirdNET on short 10-minute recordings took 10 h, with both analysis and validation of the detections, demonstrating the efficiency of automated analysis for quick surveys. However, BirdNET on all recordings amounted to 100 h, underscoring the extensive time commitment needed for a comprehensive analysis of longer recordings. Despite the longer analysis time, when comparing the total time, costs of equipment or fieldwork, and the larger species numbers detected in PAM, BirdNET proved to be a reliable tool for large-scale monitoring, offering a balance between efficiency and coverage in species detection.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0165" view="all">Each of the methods tested has its strengths, making them suitable for different monitoring objectives. Point counts, while requiring more time in the field, provide valuable insights into species distribution and abundance or better detect species that rarely vocalise and are instead observed visually. In contrast, PAM recordings offer versatile applications, ranging from a general overview of species composition obtained through automated analysis or observer interpretation to a more detailed analysis of vocal characteristics of species within a given area. Therefore, researchers should select their survey methods based on their specific objectives, available time, and financial capabilities, carefully weighing the trade-offs between the detailed observations provided by traditional observer-based methods and the efficiency and scalability of automated detection software such as BirdNET. Choosing the most appropriate method allows researchers to optimise their monitoring efforts and ensure the most accurate, cost-effective data collection tailored to their specific study goals.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="s0045" view="all">
                  <ce:label>5</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="st065">Conclusion</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0170" view="all">Our study underscores the importance of selecting the appropriate bird monitoring method based on the study’s specific goals. While traditional observer-based methods provide valuable insights into general species composition, especially for species that are visually identifiable or infrequently vocalise, automated analysis methods offer significant advantages in terms of efficiency and scalability. Automated approaches can capture a broader range of species over extended periods (80 species compared to the next most effective recording analysis with 61 species), making them well-suited for large-scale and long-term monitoring programs. However, a concerning finding was the weak correlation between species counts obtained during short sampling periods and the total species detected during all-day recordings (r = 0.34–0.49). This raises concerns about the effectiveness of short-duration surveys, especially in species-rich habitats such as primaeval forests, where they may not capture the full biodiversity. Because we relied on the first true detection of each species, we may have overlooked new species misidentified by the algorithm, potentially underestimating the overall richness in Białowieża forest. Additionally, the performance of BirdNET depends on the availability of sufficient samples for each species, which may impact detection accuracy for rarer species. Future research should explore cumulative surveys, where repeated recordings over time would help improve species detection rates and identify species that may have been missed in initial surveys in varying field conditions or various habitats. Ultimately, our findings highlight the potential of automated approaches for large-scale and long-term monitoring, while also recognising the need for further improvements in detection and analysis.</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="s0050" view="all">
                  <ce:section-title id="st070">CRediT authorship contribution statement</ce:section-title>
